{
  "texts": [
    "The assumption underlying the administration of psychological tests is that the responses provided by test takers are the result of specific processes that align with the construct of interest.",
    "These cognitive processes and strategies are challenging to investigate for both human and LLM test takers, and can at best be approximated.",
    "Consequently, it remains unclear whether the internal response processes of humans and large language models are comparable at all, which makes the use of methods designed to isolate, trigger, and analyze human cognitive processes potentially unsuitable for large language models.",
    "The current approaches to address reliability (R1), suitability (R3) and non-disclosure of test materials (R4) heavily rely on modifications of the original test items.",
    "Reliability is often measured by comparing the original test to variants of it, i.e."
  ]
}